{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775887442268,"sessionID":"ses_284dc67edffeQA8vXFiu99qzyB","part":{"id":"prt_d7b23de2e001NMKjay7kBXKmrC","messageID":"msg_d7b23d3b4001Rv3eAPb6Ep5EYS","sessionID":"ses_284dc67edffeQA8vXFiu99qzyB","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bc650533fd7d49bdb247d937","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/docs/docs/guides/architecture.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/docs/docs/guides/architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: id: architecture\n3: title: Architecture Overview\n4: description: Understanding the AgentCube architecture\n5: sidebar_position: 1\n6: ---\n7: \n8: # Architecture Overview\n9: \n10: AgentCube is built with a microservices architecture designed for scalability, reliability, and maintainability. This document provides an in-depth look at each component.\n11: \n12: ## High-Level Architecture\n13: \n14: ```mermaid\n15: graph TB\n16:     subgraph Clients\n17:         A[Web App]\n18:         B[Mobile App]\n19:         C[API Client]\n20:     end\n21:     \n22:     subgraph Gateway\n23:         D[Load Balancer]\n24:     end\n25:     \n26:     subgraph Core\n27:         E[Router]\n28:         F[Agent Runtime]\n29:         G[Code Interpreter]\n30:     end\n31:     \n32:     subgraph Storage\n33:         H[(PostgreSQL)]\n34:         I[(Redis)]\n35:         J[S3]\n36:     end\n37:     \n38:     subgraph Management\n39:         K[Workload Manager]\n40:         L[Session Routing]\n41:     end\n42:     \n43:     A --> D\n44:     B --> D\n45:     C --> D\n46:     D --> E\n47:     E --> F\n48:     F --> G\n49:     F --> H\n50:     F --> I\n51:     G --> I\n52:     K --> F\n53:     L --> E\n54: ```\n55: \n56: ## Core Components\n57: \n58: ### Router\n59: \n60: The Router is the entry point for all requests. It handles:\n61: \n62: - **Request routing**: Directs requests to appropriate agent runtimes\n63: - **Load balancing**: Distributes load across multiple instances\n64: - **Rate limiting**: Prevents abuse and ensures fair usage\n65: - **Authentication**: Validates API keys and tokens\n66: \n67: ```go\n68: // Router configuration\n69: type RouterConfig struct {\n70:     Port         int\n71:     MaxConns     int\n72:     Timeout      time.Duration\n73:     RateLimit    RateLimitConfig\n74:     TLS          TLSConfig\n75: }\n76: ```\n77: \n78: ### Agent Runtime\n79: \n80: The Agent Runtime is the core execution environment for AI agents. It manages:\n81: \n82: - **Agent lifecycle**: Creation, execution, and termination\n83: - **Session management**: Maintains state across interactions\n84: - **Tool execution**: Runs agent tools (code interpreter, etc.)\n85: - **Error handling**: Implements retry logic and fallback strategies\n86: \n87: ```go\n88: type AgentRuntime struct {\n89:     ID           string\n90:     Name         string\n91:     Model        string\n92:     Instructions string\n93:     Tools        []Tool\n94:     State        AgentState\n95: }\n96: ```\n97: \n98: ### Code Interpreter\n99: \n100: The Code Interpreter provides secure code execution capabilities:\n101: \n102: - **Sandboxed execution**: Code runs in isolated containers\n103: - **Multiple languages**: Python, JavaScript, Go support\n104: - **Resource limits**: CPU, memory, and time constraints\n105: - **Output capture**: Stdout, stderr, and file outputs\n106: \n107: ### Session Store\n108: \n109: The Session Store handles persistent session data:\n110: \n111: - **PostgreSQL**: Primary data store for sessions and metadata\n112: - **Redis**: Caching layer for fast access\n113: - **Automatic cleanup**: Removes idle sessions\n114: \n115: ### Session Routing\n116: \n117: The Session Routing component ensures session affinity:\n118: \n119: - **Sticky sessions**: Routes requests to the same runtime\n120: - **Load distribution**: Balances across runtimes\n121: - **Failover**: Handles runtime failures gracefully\n122: \n123: ### Workload Manager\n124: \n125: The Workload Manager orchestrates agent workloads:\n126: \n127: - **Scaling**: Adds/removes runtime instances\n128: - **Placement**: Optimizes resource allocation\n129: - **Monitoring**: Tracks performance metrics\n130: \n131: ## Data Flow\n132: \n133: 1. **Request received** → Router validates and authenticates\n134: 2. **Routing** → Session Routing determines target runtime\n135: 3. **Execution** → Agent Runtime processes the request\n136: 4. **Tool call** → Code Interpreter executes code if needed\n137: 5. **Response** → Results returned to client\n138: 6. **State saved** → Session state persisted\n139: \n140: ## Scaling\n141: \n142: AgentCube supports horizontal scaling at each layer:\n143: \n144: - **Router**: Multiple instances behind load balancer\n145: - **Runtime**: Auto-scaling based on load\n146: - **Storage**: PostgreSQL read replicas\n147: - **Cache**: Redis cluster mode\n148: \n149: ## Security\n150: \n151: Security features include:\n152: \n153: - **TLS encryption**: All communications encrypted\n154: - **API keys**: Per-agent authentication\n155: - **Sandboxing**: Isolated execution environments\n156: - **Audit logging**: All actions logged\n157: \n158: ## Monitoring\n159: \n160: Each component exposes metrics:\n161: \n162: - **Request rate**: Requests per second\n163: - **Latency**: P50, P95, P99 response times\n164: - **Error rate**: Failed requests percentage\n165: - **Resource usage**: CPU, memory, network\n166: \n167: ## Next Steps\n168: \n169: - [Configuration Guide](/docs/guides/configuration)\n170: - [Monitoring Guide](/docs/guides/monitoring)\n171: - [API Reference](/docs/api/agent-runtime)\n\n(End of file - total 171 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nid: architecture\ntitle: Architecture Overview\ndescription: Understanding the AgentCube architecture\nsidebar_position: 1\n---\n\n# Architecture Overview\n\nAgentCube is built with a microservices architecture designed for scalability, reliability, and maintainability. This document provides an in-depth look at each component.\n\n## High-Level Architecture\n\n```mermaid\ngraph TB\n    subgraph Clients\n        A[Web App]\n        B[Mobile App]\n        C[API Client]\n    end","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/docs/docs/guides/architecture.md","time":{"start":1775887442257,"end":1775887442265}}}}
